{"id":"1508.02917","submitter":"Mark Panaggio Mark Panaggio","authors":"Mark J. Panaggio, Daniel M. Abrams, Peter Ashwin and Carlo R. Laing","title":"Chimera states in networks of phase oscillators: the case of two small\n  populations","comments":"13 pages, 16 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 93, 012218 (2016)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.93.012218","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.PS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Chimera states are dynamical patterns in networks of coupled oscillators in\nwhich regions of synchronous and asynchronous oscillation coexist. Although\nthese states are typically observed in large ensembles of oscillators and\nanalyzed in the continuum limit, chimeras may also occur in systems with finite\n(and small) numbers of oscillators. Focusing on networks of $2N$ phase\noscillators that are organized in two groups, we find that chimera states,\ncorresponding to attracting periodic orbits, appear with as few as two\noscillators per group and demonstrate that for $N>2$ the bifurcations that\ncreate them are analogous to those observed in the continuum limit. These\nfindings suggest that chimeras, which bear striking similarities to dynamical\npatterns in nature, are observable and robust in small networks that are\nrelevant to a variety of real-world systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 12 Aug 2015 13:47:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-02-03"}
